<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-952-338  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 952 338.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Systems News  Dec 11 1989 n447 p3(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>High-end exports imperiled; fed supercomputer definition may limitsales of other high-powered systems.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Peterson, Stacey.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A draft government regulation defining a supercomputer as anymachine with a theoretical peak performance of 100 MFLOPS orgreater could hamper exports of high-end mainframe computers,minisupercomputers and workstations.andP;  The government regulatessupercomputer exports because their potential military uses couldthreaten national security.andP;  While few machines right now run atthe 100 MFLOPS level, by mid-1990, virtually all machines shallrun at 200 MFLOPS or greater.andP;  If the proposed definition isadopted, all machines that fall under the supercomputer categorywill undergo a thorough review process that could delay exports.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ExportGovernment RegulationSupercomputersInternationalSalesForeign CompetitionPerformance Specifications.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>